  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It is a serious financial crime that is often associated with other criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and organized crime.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, among other statutes. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Severe fines**: Individuals and organizations can face substantial monetary penalties.\n- **Imprisonment**: Convictions can result in lengthy prison sentences, often up to **20 years or more** per count, depending on the severity and scope of the crime.\n- **Asset forfeiture**: Authorities may seize assets connected to the illegal activity.\n\nThe specific penalties depend on the amount of money laundered, the underlying criminal activity, and whether the defendant has prior convictions. Additionally, international money laundering is prosecuted under treaties and agreements between countries.\n\nIf you are facing such charges, it is crucial to seek legal counsel immediately.",
